hands_on_practices.solution:
We have two identical atoms of mass $m$, reduced mass $\mu=m/2$, interacting via

$$
V_{\text{eff}}(r)
=\frac{l(l+1)\hbar^2}{2\mu r^2}-\frac{C_6}{r^6},
\quad l=2.
$$

1.  Locate the barrier by $dV_{\text{eff}}/dr=0$:

$$
\frac{d}{dr}\Bigl(\frac{a}{r^2}-\frac{C_6}{r^6}\Bigr)
=-\frac{2a}{r^3}+\frac{6C_6}{r^7}=0,
\quad a=\frac{l(l+1)\hbar^2}{2\mu}= \frac{6\hbar^2}{2\mu}= \frac{3\hbar^2}{\mu}.
$$

Solving gives

$$
r_{\max}^4=\frac{3C_6}{a}
=\frac{3C_6}{3\hbar^2/\mu}
=\frac{\mu\,C_6}{\hbar^2},
\quad
r_{\max}=\Bigl(\frac{\mu\,C_6}{\hbar^2}\Bigr)^{1/4}.
$$

2.  Evaluate the barrier height $V_{\max}=V_{\text{eff}}(r_{\max})$:

$$
V_{\max}
=\frac{a}{r_{\max}^2}-\frac{C_6}{r_{\max}^6}
=\frac{3\hbar^2/\mu}{(\mu C_6/\hbar^2)^{1/2}}
-\frac{C_6}{(\mu C_6/\hbar^2)^{3/2}}
=\frac{2\,\hbar^3}{\mu^{3/2}C_6^{1/2}}.
$$

Substitute $\mu=m/2$:

$$
\mu^{3/2}=\Bigl(\frac{m}{2}\Bigr)^{3/2}=\frac{m^{3/2}}{2^{3/2}}
=\frac{m^{3/2}}{2\sqrt2}
\;\;\Longrightarrow\;\;
V_{\max}
=\frac{2\hbar^3}{(m^{3/2}/2\sqrt2)\,C_6^{1/2}}
=\frac{4\sqrt2\,\hbar^3}{m^{3/2}\,C_6^{1/2}}.
$$

3.  The minimum temperature $T_{\min}$ satisfies $k_B T_{\min}=V_{\max}$, hence

$$
T_{\min}
=\frac{V_{\max}}{k_B}
=\frac{4\sqrt2\,\hbar^3}{k_B\,m^{3/2}\,C_6^{1/2}}.
$$
